cities <- read_csv("../data/largest_cities.csv")
cities

us <- read_csv("../data/us_city_population.csv")
us

Please refer to the previous notebooks for more information about these data sets and how these data sets are organized.

1.1 Selecting rows and columns

Take the cities data set and select only the first 5 rows. (Note: for this and other questions in the notebook, just write the code to produce the required data. There is no need to save the results as a variable unless specifically asked to)

cities |>
  slice(1:5)

Now, filter the data set to include only those cities with a population (population) over 10 million people.

cities |>
  filter(population > 10)

How many cities have a population over 10 million people? Answer: 33

In the code block below, extract the cities that have between 7 and 10 million people.

cities |>
  filter(between(population, 7, 10))

How many cities have a population between 7 and 10 million people? Answer: 18

In the code block below, extract the cities in Asia that have between 7 and 10 million people

cities |>
  filter(between(population, 7, 10)) |>
  filter(continent %in% c("Asia"))

How many Asian cities have a population between 7 and 10 million people? Answer: 15

1.2 Filtering plot

Take the data set us. Select only the year 1800 and remove rows that have a population of zero.

us |>
  filter(year == 1800) |>
  filter(population > 0)

How many cities have a non-zero population given for the year 1800? Answer: 22

Now, starting with the data set you produced in the last chunk of code, produce a plot with city on the x-axis and and population on the y-axis using the geom_col layer:

us |>
  filter(year == 1800) |>
  filter(population > 0) |>
  ggplot(aes(city, population)) +
  geom_col()

You will notice that the labels are too difficult to read because they run into one another. Modify this plot in the code block below by flipping the x and y aesthetics:

us |>
  filter(year == 1800) |>
  filter(population > 0) |>
  ggplot(aes(population, city)) +
  geom_col()

How easy do you find this plot to read? What improvements might you want to make to it? (Donâ€™t worry about what you can do right now; think about what would make it easier to interpret). Answer: I find it relatively easy to read, though it would be good to re-order the data in a more meaningful way, such as from the largest to the smallest city.

1.3 Arranging rows

In the code below, extract the five European cities from cities that have the largest population. (Note: this will take three different verbs).

cities |>
  filter(continent == "Europe") |>
  arrange(desc(population)) |>
  slice(1:5)

Which European city in our data set has the largest population? Answer: Istanbul (though, technically much of the city is actually in Asia).

1.4 Selecting columns

Take the cities data set and filter only those cities in Africa and Europe. Use the select function to see just the city name and the variable koppen_code.

cities |>
  filter(continent %in% c("Africa", "Europe")) |>
  select(name, koppen_code)

1.5 Layering graphics

In the code below, create a data set called cities_large_metro by extracting the rows of cities that have a metro region larger than the U.N. estimate of the cityâ€™s population.

cities_large_metro <- cities |>
  filter(population < metro_pop)

Now, draw a scatter plot with longitude on the x-axis and latitude on the y-axis. Show all of the rows in the data set using a light grey color. Then, add points layer and a text layer (with the city names as labels) for the rows in cities_large_metro. Pick a bold color for the points and labels.

cities |>
  ggplot(aes(lon, lat)) +
  geom_point(color = "grey85") +
  geom_point(color = "olivedrab", data = cities_large_metro) +
  geom_text_repel(aes(label = name), color = "olivedrab", data = cities_large_metro)

Do you see any particular patterns about which cities have metropolitan regions that are larger than the cityâ€™s official U.N.-listed population? (Note: There is at least one thing that becomes apparent, but you will probably not find something that explains all of the data). Answer: While there are cities in all of the major continents, there is a particular concentration of cities with large metro areas in the United States.

1.6 A better bar plot

Letâ€™s now try to build a better bar plot. In the next code chunk, take the us dataset, filter to just the year 1800 and cities with a non-zero population, and arrange the cities by their population:

us |>
  filter(year == 1800) |>
  filter(population > 0) |>
  arrange(population)

Now, starting with the code from the previous chunk, draw a plot using geom_col, with population mapped to the x-axis and city mapped to the y-axis. You will notice that this is no different from the previous plot you made above.

us |>
  filter(year == 1800) |>
  filter(population > 0) |>
  arrange(population) |>
  ggplot(aes(population, city)) +
  geom_col()

Copy the code from above but wrap the variable city in the function fct_inorder when setting it to the y aesthetic.

us |>
  filter(year == 1800) |>
  filter(population > 0) |>
  arrange(population) |>
  ggplot(aes(population, fct_inorder(city))) +
  geom_col() +
  geom_text(aes(population + 3, fct_inorder(city), label = population), size = 3)

You should now notice that the cities are arranged by population. We will talk more about this function in future notes.
